Q25_7_TEXT: As far as I know, no e-scooter company is operating in the black.  It means that venture capitalists are subsidizing the cost of riding e-scooters.  If we had a rational market, that subsidy would not be permitted and riders would have to pay the actual cost per mile of using the scooters.  In that case, the enterprises would die because few people would want to pay that much. They are unwanted products of the Silicon Valley culture that never considers the unanticipated negative consequences of the "disruptive" technology it creates.  In this case, the e-scooter companies exploit workers by treating them as contractors, which they clearly are not (I was a member of the Oregon Bar for 30 years and I know this stuff), so the people who collect, power and distribute these devices are not receivig any benefits (including social security contributions or workers compensation) and they may not even be earning minimum wage.  Considering how many scooters end up in the Willamette River, it should be noted that their batteries make them environmental hazzards.  Finally, because the City of Portland will not enforce the rules for riding e-scooters, e-scooter riders endanger pedestrians by riding illegally on sidewalks and in parks, and they endanger themselves by not wearing helmets and by riding doubles.  I want nothing to do with this.
